
[1]pillow

   PIL'LOW, n. [L. pulvinar; from L. pilus, hair, or from stuffing.]

   1. A long cushion to support the head of a person when reposing on a
   bed; a sack or case filled with feathers, down or other soft material.

   2. In a ship, the block on which the inner end of a bowsprit is
   supported.

   The pillow of a plow, is a cross piece of wood which serves to raise or
                               lower the beam.

                PIL'LOW, v.t. To rest or lay on for support.
